⬇️ RECIPE ⬇️Filipino Bistek. To me, this is the most simple and most tasty meal you can make. And there’s  nothing subtle about this dish. A delightful combination of tangy, sweet, savory, peppery garlicky flavors- This dish will reach up and punch you in the mouth – in a really good way. Filipino Bistek (or Beef steak) is a traditional dish using thinly sliced beef marinaded in a potion of soy calamansi citrus garlic onion sauce, all of it  stir fried, sauteed and topped with an ungodly amount of delicious onions rings. Serve it over a bed of fluffy white rice -  and it’s magic for your mouth. You have got to try it. All ingredients bought fresh from @islandpacificmarket 
▪ 1.5 lb thinly sliced rib eye
▪ ½ cup soy sauce
▪ ¼ cup lemon or calamansi juice
▪ 1sp each of black pepper, garlic powder, corn starch, sugar
▪ Marinade the beef for at least an hour.
▪ Sear the beef on high heat in small batches, remove from pan.
▪ Sautee a whole minced garlic, then add a whole sliced onion (rings).
▪ Then add the beef back in and mix thoroughly, adding remaining marinade until desired consistency. Serve with rice and devour like an animal.  #homecooks #foodies #filipinocook #easyrecipes #easycooking #foryourpage #freshfood #easymeal #filipinofood #bistektagalog

LIKE if you want HelloFresh to add Filipino flavors! I love HelloFresh since they make dinner prep so easy. With back-to-school season, avoiding shopping and stores saves so much time, which I was able to do with this Filipino reimagined recipe for Honey Butter BBQ Pork Chops. All the HelloFresh ingredients delivered were great, but I made just a couple simple substitutes to twist the standard and make it a Filipino inspired Hello “Presh” meal. For the mashed potatoes, instead of butter I added @gobigboi ensaymada sweet butter which has savory shredded cheese. For the string beans, instead of lemon zest, I added soy, vinegar and @mamasitasrecipes adobo seasoning for that distinctive tangy soy, garlic, pepper flavor we know and love. And for the pork chops, instead of the BBQ seasoning, I again used the Mamasita adobo seasoning for a zesty kick to a seared adobo pork chops. With just a few easy tweaks, I tailored the HelloFresh recipe and gave it a Filipino twist with flavors we all know, and others can discover and love. You got to try it! @hellofresh #hellofresh #skipthestore #homecooks #foodies #filipinofood #filipinocook #easyrecipes #easycooking #foryourpage #freshfood #easymeal

⬇️RECIPE ⬇️Kare Kare is not as popular as lumpia, pancit, adobo, but it’s absolutely a must-try on the Filipino menu. It’s a bit more complex with a deep thick rich stew filled with all sorts of vegetables and meat like ox tail, plus it’s seasoned with shrimp paste and peanut butter! But it’s so worth stepping out of your comfort zone and experiencing something new and delicious. You got try it, and here’s how you can make it:
In my Instant Pot I added and seared:
• Diced whole onion and garlic
• 1 Tbsp each of Atsuete powder (Anatto), bagaong shrimp paste, black pepper, sea salt, sugar
• ½ cup of finely ground roasted peanuts
• ½ cup Jiffy peanut butter
• 2 packets of Mamasitas Kare Kare mix
• 10 cups of broth or water. Bring to a boil.
In a separate pan, season and sear on high heat 3 lbs of short rib until nice crust, then add to broth in Instant Pot and set to High for 50 minutes until ribs are just fall-off-the-bone tender.
Veggies, 1 LB each of:
• Chinese eggplant, sliced
• Sitaw (or green beans)
• Bok Choy
• Oil season SPG and broil until tender and slightly charred
In a sizzling hot cast iron pan, add some broth, layer in the short ribs and veggies, a cup of rice, top with more bagaong, then slather with more broth. #homecooks #foodies #filipinofood #filipinocook #easyrecipes #easycooking #foryourpage #freshfood #easymeal #karekare #shortribs

⬇️SAVE for Labor Day BBQ ⬇️ Just in time for your Labor Day get-together, these Baby back ribs are a perfect Filipino twist to classic BBQ ribs. I pressure steamed them in an adobo broth, infusing them with all the adobo flavors, then coated them with a banana ketchup BBQ glaze before I broiled them to sticky crusty fall off the bone perfection. You got to try it! Ingredients bought fresh from @islandpacificmarket 
o 2 full racks of baby back ribs (spareribs will work too)
o Season generously both sides with sea salt, pepper, garlic powder
o Add the following into a pressure cooker (or Pot).
• ½ cup soy
• ½ cup vinegar
• 1 whole garlic (peeling optional)
• 1 whole onion (cut in quarter)
• 3 bay leaves
• 2 Tbsp. of liquid smoke (optional but gives a nice smoke BBQ flavor)​
o Place ribs on rack on top of the broth, and pressure cook high for 20 minutes which will steam infuse flavor into ribs while tenderizing. ​
o Prepare BBQ Filipino Glaze:
• ½ cup BBQ Sauce (I love #sweetbabyRays)
• ½ cup banana ketchup
• ½ cup brown sugar
• 1 Tbsp. liquid smoke (optional but gives a nice smoke BBQ flavor)
• 1 tsp garlic powder
• 1 Tbsp. soy sauce
• Heat optional (red pepper flakes, cayenne)
o Remove ribs from pot, place on rack, and slather the sauce generously over both sides.
o Broil 550 on medium rack for about 5 minutes, watching closely to avoid burning.
o Remove when glaze is bubbling and caramelized.
o Serve remaining sauce with ribs.

⬇️RECIPE ⬇️ Filipino Adobo Wings. These winner-winner chicken dinner Adobo wings are a rappers delight and a great easy way to pregame on the first weekend of the #nflfootball football season 🏈🏈🏈Here’s how to make.
 
- 2 lbs chicken wings parboiled 8 minutes in below adobo sauce:
- 1/2 cups each of soy sauce and vinegar
- 1Tbspns each of of pepper, garlic and onion powder
- 3 bay leaves.
- Remove chicken from sauce and let dry on rack.
- Then in your @breville air fry @ 425 for 15 minutes, flipping at 7 minutes.
- Prepare adobo glaze by using remaining adobo sauce thickened with corn starch, 4 Tbsp. brown sugar, and 2 Tbsp. butter. Put the wings in a bowl, add the glaze and toss to coat (on beat if you got some). Serve with rice and #atcharangpapaya . The very best chicken wings! ⬇️FOLLOW FOR RECIPES⬇️ Sinigang is a tangy Filipino soup which some claim acts as an aphrodisiac😉 that I love to overload with veggies like these carrots, diced fresh tomatoes, onion, garlic, green beans and tons of spinach. I season with SPG and give the pork a hard sear, then boil for about 20 minutes to soften and render out some fat. I also like to char the string beans in the same pan as the pork which gives them a great color and flavor. Just a bit better than simply boiling IMHO. I love using tamarind paste for an extra tamarind punch and has a little sweetened, and never forget the #mamasitas sinigang season packet. Sinigang’s normally eaten with rice, but I love it with sotanghon mung bean noodle, which are these fun tasty glassy slippery springy noodles. They absorb the broth but don’t get mushy like rice tends to. You got to try it!
• 2 lbs pork belly cut into cubes. Season SPG, the high heat sear all sides. Boil for at least 20 minutes to render out fat and tenderize. Drain.
• In the same pan sear about 1 lb of string beans or sitaw until slightly charred and softened.
• To a pot sear 1 whole onion diced and 1 garlic minced.
• Add about 10-cups of water or broth deglaze pot.
• Add 2 Tbspn patis fish sauce, 2 Tbspn tamarind concentrate, 1 packet of Sinigang seasoning.
• Add seared pork and boil for about 30 minutes or until pork is super tender.
• Then add veggies:
• 1 lb of seared green beans (sitaw if you have it).
• 2 diced roma tomatoes
• 1 large carrots julienne
• 1 package of spinach (don’t overcook the veggies they’ll get mushy – which I hate longest and when they’re al dente add the rest which cook quickly)
• In a separate pot boil sotnghon noodles either in seasoned water or with some of the sinigang broth for maximum flavor.
• Taste and season to preference.

👍🏽LIKE and FOLLOW for Recipes 👍🏽 You may not have tried it, but Afritada is a staple among Filipino homes. Pure hearty filling comfort stew made with chicken or pork, tender potatoes, carrots, bell peppers, all mingling and tingling in a thick tomato broth accented with of all things – hot dogs! But it works …so well…and you got to try it.
✅SAVE and SHARE this Recipe✅ Here’s how to make this traditional Filipino hearty stew of either chicken or pork I used pork) in a thick and hearty tomato-based stew with vegetable and yes hot dogs (sausage if you’re fancy).
• 3 lbs pork shoulder. Seasoned w salt pepper garlic powder, cubed and seared. I use the broiler since I’m lazy.
• Whole garlic and onion minced and sauté. Then add:
o 3 Roma tomatoes cubed
o 12 oz can of tomato sauce
o 3 bay leaves
o 1 Tbsp chicken bouillon and sugar, and ½ Tbsp black pepper,
o Add pork and simmer for at least 1 hour until very tender.
• Then season and sear and add to above stew:
o 2 large carrots chopped
o 2 large potatoes chopped
o 1 -2 hot dogs (sausage) chopped
o When potatoes and carrots are tender, add 3 Tbsp canned or frozen peas.
o Add corn starch slurry to thicken if needed.
• Serve with rice and devour!

So I turn to our ancestors tangy cure-all Sinigang trusting in its mystical power for some relief. I overload it with healthy veggies and serve it over #topramen, increasing its hearty magic as a Sinigang Noodle soup. And our ancient brew always provides instant comfort and relief.
⬇️Save and Share Recipe ⬇️
• 2 lbs pork belly cut into cubes. Boil for at least 20 minutes to render out fat and tenderize. Drain fry over high heat until seared and some browning.
• Add and sear 1 whole onion diced and ½ garlic minced with the pork.
• Add about 10-cups of water or broth deglaze pot. (add more if needed adjusting seasoning).
• Add 2 Tbspn patis fish sauce, 1 Tbspn tamarind concentrate, 1 packet of Sinigang seasoning. Boil for about 30 minutes or until pork is super tender.
• Then add the following veggies in order:
• 1 lb of green beans (sitaw if you have it). I like to sear mine over high heat until slight blistered. Adds nice texture and flavor.
• 2 diced roma tomatos
• 2 carrots jullien
• 1 package of spinach (don’t overcook the veggies they’ll get mushy – which I hate so add the green beans first since they take the longest and when they’re al dente add the rest which cook quickly)
• Taste and season to preference.
I served mine over 1 package of cooked Top Ramen noodles. 🩶 Like and Follow for more Recipes 🩶 In the global noodle hall of fame, there’s a special place for the many Filipino pancits. This one is made with bihon rice noodles and is an all-star favorite. 
 
⬇️ Save and Share Recipe ⬇️
• 1 bag of Bihon noodles, soak in warm water while prepping everything else.
• 1 lb. of protein, I used cubed pork belly.
• 2 carrots, julienne
• 1 Chinese sausage, thinly sliced
• 1 whole garlic minced
• ¼ lb. green beans sliced
• ½ an onion, sliced
• ½ head of cabbage chopped
Make sauce:
• 2 cups chicken broth (or 2 tsp chicken bouillon in water)
• 2 Tbsps. of Soy and Oyster sauce
• 1 tsp of salt and pepper, and fish sauce to taste.
Sear pork, set aside
Sear onions, garlic, and Chinese sausage. Then add in carrots, green beans, and cabbage. Add a 1 Tbspn+ of sauce to steam and flavor veggies. Mix well.
Add the softened Bihon noodles, and seared pork belly.
Add remainder of pancit Sauce, ,and mix well until all flavors are well incorporated. Season to taste. #homecooks #foodies #filipinofood #filipinocook #easyrecipes #easycooking #foryourpage #freshfood #easymeal

Like and Follow for More. Filipino American History celebrates and recognizes our long history of influence in America. Our cultural contributions are many and far-reaching, and my contribution can be sharing of that all important part of our culture, our food which continually evolves and adapts while retaining at it’s core the connection to our families and history. This Pork Belly Adobo is a bit of a twist on the standard. I used chunks of pork belly, seasoned, fried for crust, then braised until super soft and tender.
Save and Share the Recipe:
• 2 lbs pork belly (no skin). Cut into chunks and season SPG
• Fry all sides until a nice crust is formed then andremove from oil.
• Sear ½ diced onion and 1 minced head of garlic. Then add the adobo marinade:
• ½ cup soy, ¼ cup vinegar (I used datu puti spiced seasoned vinegar for a little umph), 3 whole bay leaves, 1 tsp cracked black pepper or whole peppercorn, 1 Tbspn brown sugar, ½ cup water.
• Lid the pan and place in pre heated oven at 400 degrees to braise about 30 minutes, until super tender.
• Remove from oven add the remaining ½ onion slices and mix until onion reaches your desired tenderness. I like mine al dente with some crisp bite in them. Serve with rice and devour. #homecooks #foodies #filipinofood #filipinocook #easyrecipes #foryourpage #filipinoadobo #porkbelly #filipinoamericanhistorymonth #fahm

Like and Follow for More. Dugo means blood, and dinuguan is a stew braised in pork blood, with cubed pork and strong flavors. Some might consider it higher on the extreme exotic scale because of the blood and the black finish of the broth. Others like me just love it! There’s not much that compares to it, and it’s not commonly available, which makes it more special when it’s served. I like my dinuguan like I love my wife, thicc and dark ♥️ Some prefer smaller cubed pork, I like mine chunkier, some like soupy broth I like mine fairly thick, and the more moreno the dish the more deelish! Am I right? All ingredients available fresh from @islandpacificmarket 
Cooking up this dish was all the more special draped in my special black barong from my friends @shopbarongandformal . They have great options from formal to casual, for ladies and gents, and are great to work with. Check out their page and follow them for more barong ideas.
Save and Share Recipe
• ½ lb of liquid pork blood mixed very well with 2 Tbspn vinegar to remove and prevent clotting. Set aside.
• Mince and sear half onion and whole garlic.
• In same pan, add seasoned cubed pork belly (1.5 lbs). Mix and sear thoroughly.
• Add enough water to cover pork, then cover pan and boil at least 30 minutes until liquid evaporates.
• When liquid evaporates, stir fry until nicely seared and browned.
• Add ½ cup vinegar, then add prepared blood slowly, stirring often to maintain smooth consistency.
• Season to taste but basics are 1 tsp each of black pepper, pork bouillion (or chicken), patis fish sauce, sugar, 3 whole bay leave, chilis (I used 3 thai chilis).
• Cover and braise until pork is super soft and tender, approx. 30 minutes. Add water as necessary to achieve desired consistency.
• Serve with rice, or put@ rice cakes if you got em.

Exceptionally delicious! Use my code “BOBBYGEATS” to get 20% off your order (link can also be found in my bio).
 
Save and Share Recipe
1 Can of Natural Catch Tuna (I used the Spicy Chili flavor)
1 Tbspn each of Kewpie Mayo, Sriracha, Cream Cheese, Mirin, Furikakae
Mix the tuna and the above sauce.
 
1 cup of cooked short grain rice
1 Tbspn each of Mirin and Furikake
Mix rice and sauce.
 
Lay tuna mic on top of rice, add ½ chopped avodaco, and sprinkley more Furikake.

There are probably 7,000 ways to make Filipino Adobo (that’s the number of Islands of the Philippines). This is just one. My 123 Method refers to the ratio between vinegar, soy sauce, and water to reach what I think is the perfect balance of flavors and thickness for my Adobo. With 2 lbs of pork I use 1/3 cup as the base. More meat I’d go up to ½ cup, less then ¼ cup. And if you like more broth or more dry, then adjust. I add sugar at the end not just to make it sweet, but to further balance the other strong flavors. I also love to add veggies, this time onions. Not really traditional but delish.
